    "content": "# 文件: D:\\files\\demo\\0312-newagent\\agent-alpha\\temp\\fetch_results\\fetch_results\\4a415dcc.txt\n# 显示: 第 1291-1381 行 / 共 1381 行\n1291→Peer review\n1292→Peer review information\n1293→Nature Reviews Neuroscience\n1294→thanks L. Melloni, C. Sergent and the other, anonymous, reviewer(s) for their contribution to the peer review of this work.\n1295→Additional information\n1296→Publisher’s note\n1297→Springer Nature remains neutral with regard to jurisdictional claims in published maps and institutional affiliations.\n1298→Glossary\n1299→Neural correlates of consciousness\n1300→(NCCs). The minimal set of neural events that is jointly sufficient for a conscious state.\n1301→Explanatory gap intuitions\n1302→Intuitions that there is no prospect of a fully satisfying explanation of consciousness in physical, mechanistic terms.\n1303→Adversarial collaborations\n1304→Research projects in which proponents of different theories together design an experiment to distinguish their preferred theories, and agree in advance about how the outcome will favour one theory over the other(s).\n1305→Global states\n1306→Relating to an organism’s overall state of consciousness, usually linked to arousal and behavioural responsiveness, and associated with the ‘level’ of consciousness.\n1307→Local states\n1308→Relating to particular conscious mental states, such as a conscious perception, emotion or thought. Local states are also often called conscious contents.\n1309→Binocular rivalry\n1310→A phenomenon in which different images are presented to each eye, and conscious perception alternates between the two images.\n1311→Phenomenal character\n1312→The experiential nature of a local state, such as the ‘redness’ of an experience of red or the pain of a toothache — sometimes also called qualia.\n1313→Meta-representation\n1314→A mental representation that has as its target another mental representation\n1315→No-report paradigms\n1316→Behavioural experiments in which participants do not provide subjective (verbal, behavioural) reports.\n1317→Φ\n1318→The amount of information specified by a system that is irreducible to that specified by its parts. There are many variations of Φ, each calculated differently and making different assumptions.\n1319→Posterior hot zone\n1320→A range of brain regions towards the rear of the cortex, including parietal, temporal and occipital areas, as well as regions such as the precuneus.\n1321→Complex\n1322→In integrated information theory (IIT), a subset of a physical system that underpins a maximum of irreducible integrated information.\n1323→Interoceptive predictions\n1324→Predictions about the causes of sensory signals originating from within the body (interoception refers to perception of the body ‘from within’).\n1325→Unity of consciousness\n1326→The fact that that the experiences that a single agent has at a time seem always to occur as the components of a single complex experience.\n1327→Cognitive access\n1328→A functional property whereby a mental state has access to a wide range of cognitive processes, usually including verbal and/or behavioural report.\n1329→Computational (neuro)phenomenology\n1330→The use of computational models to account for the phenomenal character of a conscious state in terms of (neural) mechanisms.\n1331→The measurement problem\n1332→The problem of identifying whether a particular mental state is conscious, or determining whether an organism or other system is, or has the capacity to be, conscious.\n1333→Cerebral organoids\n1334→Laboratory-grown neural structures that self-organize into systems with cellular and network features resembling aspects of the developing human brain.\n1335→Rights and permissions\n1336→Reprints and permissions\n1337→About this article\n1338→Cite this article\n1339→Seth, A.K., Bayne, T. Theories of consciousness.\n1340→Nat Rev Neurosci\n1341→23\n1342→, 439–452 (2022). https://doi.org/10.1038/s41583-022-00587-4\n1343→Download citation\n1344→22 March 2022\