    "reasoning_content": "The user is confused about the brain coordinate system. The previous diagram used a head outline with an eye, but the directions (anterior/posterior, dorsal/ventral, lateral/medial) don't map intuitively when you think in terms of eyes and mouth as reference points, because the human brain is bent - the brain's \"up\" isn't the same as the head's \"up\" when you're standing.\n\nLet me think about this carefully:\n\nIn human neuroanatomy, there's a tricky issue: the brain's axes vs the body's axes. For quadrupeds (dogs, rats), the brain's long axis goes front-to-back, so anterior = nose, posterior = tail, dorsal = back/top, ventral = belly/bottom. But humans stand upright, so the brain's long axis is actually tilted relative to the body's vertical axis.\n\nKey facts:\n- **Anterior (前/Rostral)** = toward the forehead/front of the head. The frontal pole.\n- **Posterior (后/Caudal)** = toward the back of the head. The occipital pole.\n- **Dorsal (背侧/Superior)** = toward the top of the head. \n- **Ventral (腹侧/Inferior)** = toward the bottom of the head/chin.\n- **Lateral (外侧)** = toward the ears/sides.\n- **Medial (内侧)** = toward the midline (the gap between the two hemispheres).\n\nThe confusion comes from: when you look at a human brain from the side, the long axis goes roughly front-to-back (anterior-posterior), but the brainstem bends down. The neuraxis is bent.\n\nFor practical purposes in reading fMRI papers:\n- \"Dorsal\" = top/superior\n- \"Ventral\" = bottom/inferior\n- \"Anterior\" = front\n- \"Posterior\" = back\n- \"Lateral\" = side (ears)\n- \"Medial\" = middle\n\nThe user wants a clearer diagram. Let me create one that uses a human head profile as reference, with the person facing LEFT (standard neuroimaging convention), clearly marking the axes with labels people can relate to their own body.\n\nI think the best approach is:\n1. Draw a head profile facing LEFT\n2. Show the brain inside\n3. Mark axes clearly with arrows\n4. Use everyday references: forehead, back of head, top of head, chin/jaw, ears, midline\n\nLet me update just that one figure in the HTML."
